Animation (transition_states)
anim <- ggplot(gapminder,
               aes(gdpPercap, lifeExp, size = pop/1000000)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = continent)) +
  scale_x_log10() +
  labs(
    size = "Population (millions)",
    x = "GDP per capita",
    y = "Life expectancy",
    color = "Continent",
    title = "Year: {closest_state}"
  ) +
  theme(text = element_text(size = 12))

anim + transition_states(year,
                         transition_length = 1,
                         state_length = 1)
 The black bubbles are a bit hard to read, the comparison would be easier with a bit more visual differentiation. — ### Questions for the static figures:

Answer: why does it make sense to have a log10 scale (scale_x_log10()) on the x axis? (hint: try to comment it out and observe the result) There are great differences in population sizes, so it makes sense to make a logoritmic scale in order for better comparisons.

Answer: In Figure 1: Who is the outlier (the richest country in 1952) far right on the x axis? The richest counrtry is in Asia

Fix Figures 1 and 2: Differentiate the continents by color, and fix the axis labels and units to be more legible (Hint: the 2.50e+08 is so called “scientific notation”. You want to eliminate it.)

